    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The use of a generic, non-assay-specific background set implies that non-observed compounds are considered in the Fisher's exact test formula, which, by definition, will always be absent from the list of metabolites of interest (of size n, Eq 1)... A clear discrepancy was observed in many of the pathway p-values when using the nonspecific vs. specific background set (Fig 2A).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper investigates how background set size and composition affect ORA p-values and false-positive pathways, but frames this as 'background set specificity' (assay-specific vs. non-assay-specific) rather than 'metabolite detection coverage.' The paper does examine metabolite detection bias via assay chemical specificity (passage 8, Fig 6), but this is distinct from the 'coverage' framing in the card. The card's framing of 'fraction of metabolites detected relative to pathway database' is not explicitly tested; instead, the paper tests background set size reduction (Fig 2C-D) and assay-specific chemical bias.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the fraction of metabolites detected (coverage) relative to the pathway database affect the distribution of ORA p-values and false-positive rates in metabolomics pathway analysis?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:42:19.585431+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_002/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Using five experimental datasets, we vary the inputs, each time comparing to the original or standard settings, thus demonstrating the effect of these choices on the output lists of significant pathways... We define two performance statistics: the pathway loss rate and the pathway gain rate.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does produce summary statistics and tables (e.g., Table 1, Table 2, Fig 2B showing number of SEPs), but the specific metrics are 'pathway loss rate' and 'pathway gain rate' (analogous to false-negative and false-positive rates), not explicitly 'false-positive rates' as a standalone metric. The paper does not explicitly report 'coverage levels' as a tabulated parameter.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Summary statistics table (CSV or TSV) with coverage levels, ORA p-value statistics, and false-positive rates",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:42:19.585431+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_002/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Fig 2 Effect of background set... Fig 5 Metabolite misidentification. The effect of compound misidentification by molecular weight (20ppm window) (bars in dark colours) and chemical formula (bars in light colours) on the mean pathway loss rate (lower bars) and mean pathway gain rate (upper bars)...",
      "asbval:note": "Paper produces figures showing pathway loss/gain rates (false-positive/negative analogues) as a function of background set size (Fig 2C-D) and metabolite misidentification (Fig 5), but not explicitly as a function of 'metabolite detection coverage.' The framing differs: paper examines background set reduction and misidentification, not coverage as a continuous variable relative to pathway database size.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Figure(s) showing false-positive rate and ORA p-value distribution as a function of metabolite detection coverage",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:42:19.585431+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_002/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "All simulations were performed using Python (v 3.8)... ORA was implemented using a custom Python script that utilised the scipy stats fisher_exact function (right-tailed) to calculate pathway p-values.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states Python v3.8 was used for simulations and ORA implementation.",
