    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_002/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card frames the research question around 'metabolite detection coverage relative to pathway database,' but the paper's actual focus is on 'background set specificity' (assay-specific vs. non-assay-specific) and 'background set size.' These are related but distinct concepts.",
        "The card emphasizes 'false-positive rates' as a key output, but the paper uses 'pathway loss rate' and 'pathway gain rate' as the primary metrics for quantifying false negatives and false positives. The paper acknowledges these are 'analogous to false-negative and false-positive rates, but account for the fact that we do not know the truly enriched pathways.'",
        "The card's framing of 'coverage' as a continuous variable is not directly tested in the paper. Instead, the paper examines discrete scenarios: assay-specific vs. non-assay-specific background sets, and simulated metabolite misidentification at fixed percentages (4%, 1\u20135%).",
        "The paper does examine assay chemical bias (Fig 6), which relates to differential metabolite detection across assay types, but this is presented as a separate analysis from background set effects, not as a unified 'coverage' parameter."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 4,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:42:19.585431+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105__task_003/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To perform ORA, three essential inputs are required: a collection of pathways (or custom metabolite sets), a list of metabolites of interest, and a background or reference set of compounds... The background set contains all molecules which can be detected in the experiment. For example, in transcriptomic studies, this consists of all genes or transcripts which can be quantified. In targeted metabolomics, the background set would contain all compounds assayed; in untargeted metabolomics, all annotatable metabolites (i.e., all the features in a dataset that can be annotated to a compound name or ID).",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly defines background set construction as a core ORA component and discusses how it is determined from experimental detection lists.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How is the background set of metabolites constructed for Over-representation Analysis (ORA) in metabolomics, given an experimental detection list and a metabolomics pathway database?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:42:41.384490+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
