    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/false-positive-rate-assessment/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The pathway loss rate represents the proportion of the original pathways (0% misidentification) significant at p \u2264 0.1 that are no longer significant at f % misidentification. The pathway gain rate represents the proportion of pathways that were not significant at 0% misidentification but become significant at f % misidentification.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper defines 'pathway gain rate' (false-positive analogue) and 'pathway loss rate' (false-negative analogue) but uses p \u2264 0.1 threshold, not p < 0.05. Paper explicitly states: 'These are analogous to false-negative and false-positive rates, but account for the fact that we do not know the truly enriched pathways.' The paper's approach is conceptually similar but uses different thresholds and acknowledges the limitation that ground truth is unknown.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "false-positive-rate-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify the proportion of statistically significant results (p < 0.05) that are false positives across a range of controlled simulation conditions in pathway analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:44:05.567619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/false-positive-rate-assessment/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our aim here, therefore, is to investigate the robustness of ORA in typical metabolomics analysis, by examining the impact of varying the input data and parameters. The factors examined are: the background set, selection of differential metabolites, pathway database choice, organism-specific pathway sets, metabolite misidentification, and chemical bias of the assay.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly investigates ORA robustness under varying conditions including background set (detection coverage proxy) and metabolite misidentification.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "false-positive-rate-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill is essential for validating the robustness of Over-representation Analysis (ORA) under varying metabolite detection coverage",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:44:05.567619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/false-positive-rate-assessment/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We simulated the effects of metabolite misidentification on ORA using KEGG pathways by replacing the true metabolites with false ones in two different ways: a) by similar molecular weight (20ppm window), and b) by identical chemical formula",
      "asbval:note": "Paper performs simulations but does NOT use null conditions (no true enrichment). Instead, paper assumes 'all pathways significant at 0% misidentification are the \"true\" SEPs' and compares to degraded versions. This is a different simulation paradigm than the card describes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "false-positive-rate-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have run ORA on simulated metabolite sets with known null conditions (no true pathway enrichment)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:44:05.567619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/false-positive-rate-assessment/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The use of a nonspecific background set, such as all compounds present in the KEGG reference or human pathway set, for example, resulted in a drastic increase in the number of SEPs... The use of a nonspecific background set resulted in large numbers of false-positive pathways.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates that background set size and pathway database choice affect false-positive rates, but does not formally quantify Type I error inflation across systematic parameter sweeps. Paper uses pathway gain/loss rates rather than formal Type I error rate calculations.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "false-positive-rate-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "measure how detection coverage, pathway database size, or other experimental parameters inflate Type I error rates",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:44:05.567619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
