      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The use of a nonspecific background set, such as all compounds present in the KEGG reference or human pathway set, for example, resulted in a drastic increase in the number of SEPs... The use of a generic, non-assay-specific background set implies that non-observed compounds are considered in the Fisher's exact test formula... Defining the ideal assay-specific background set for a particular dataset remains an area for further study.",
