    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The use of a generic, non-assay-specific background set implies that non-observed compounds are considered in the Fisher's exact test formula, which, by definition, will always be absent from the list of metabolites of interest... The use of a nonspecific background set, such as all compounds present in the KEGG reference or human pathway set, for example, resulted in a drastic increase in the number of SEPs.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper addresses how incomplete detection (via background set specification) affects ORA results and false positives, but does NOT explicitly quantify detection coverage as a fraction or model p-value distributions across coverage scenarios. The paper examines background set size effects and metabolite misidentification, but the specific research question about 'detection coverage fraction' and its systematic effect on p-value distributions is not directly addressed. The paper's focus is on parameter sensitivity, not on coverage-stratified p-value modeling.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Interpret Over-representation Analysis (ORA) p-values in metabolomics pathway analysis by quantifying how detection coverage (fraction of pathway metabolites actually measured) affects false-positive rates and statistical significance distributions.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:45:49.057619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The use of a nonspecific background set... resulted in large numbers of false-positive pathways... it is crucial however to understand that the consequence of not specifying a background set, which should contain all compounds that are realistically observable, is that an assumption is being made that the compounds in the default background set are all equally likely to be detected in the experiment. Such an assumption is highly unlikely to be true given that most technologies can only detect a small fraction of the metabolome and may lead to false-positive pathways.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly warns against false positives from incomplete detection and emphasizes the need to specify realistic background sets based on what is actually detectable.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill guards against inflated significance claims arising from incomplete metabolite detection.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:45:49.057619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our aim here, therefore, is to investigate the robustness of ORA in typical metabolomics analysis, by examining the impact of varying the input data and parameters... Varying ORA inputs can result in large changes to outputs, which raises the question of how such parameters should be chosen in order to obtain the most reliable results.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper's core aim aligns with assessing ORA robustness and parameter effects on significance.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have run ORA on a metabolomics dataset and obtained p-values for pathway enrichment, but you need to assess whether observed significance is genuine or an artifact of incomplete metabolite coverage.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:45:49.057619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "metabolomics datasets tend to cover a much lower proportion of the total metabolome than transcriptomic datasets do of the genome... In untargeted metabolomics, all annotatable metabolites (i.e., all the features in a dataset that can be annotated to a compound name or ID).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper acknowledges that metabolomics covers a small fraction of the metabolome and discusses background set size effects, but does NOT provide explicit coverage percentage ranges (e.g., '30\u201380%') or model p-value distributions across coverage scenarios. The specific quantitative framework for coverage-stratified analysis is not present.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When the fraction of detected metabolites relative to the pathway database is known or estimable (e.g., 30\u201380% coverage is common), and you want to understand how p-value distributions and false-positive rates shift across different coverage scenarios.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:45:49.057619+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/over-representation-analysis-pvalue-interpretation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "metabolomics datasets tend to cover a much lower proportion of the total metabolome than transcriptomic datasets do of the genome. Hence, metabolomics datasets tend to contain far fewer metabolites than transcripts found in transcriptomic datasets.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper acknowledges that metabolomics rarely achieves high coverage, but does NOT explicitly define a coverage threshold (e.g., >95%) above which ORA p-values become trustworthy. The claim about >95% coverage being safe is not directly supported.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
