    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-database-querying/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To perform ORA, three essential inputs are required: a collection of pathways (or custom metabolite sets), a list of metabolites of interest, and a background or reference set of compounds. Pathway sets can be obtained from several databases, for example, the Kyoto Encyclopaedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) [15], Reactome [16], and BioCyc [17] databases... The background set contains all molecules which can be detected in the experiment.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly discusses retrieving pathway databases (KEGG, Reactome, BioCyc) and constructing background sets as core ORA inputs. The research question aligns with the paper's focus on background-set definition and pathway membership.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-database-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Retrieve and structure metabolite-to-pathway mappings from a metabolomics pathway database to define the statistical background and pathway membership for Over-representation Analysis (ORA). This skill enables construction of unbiased background sets and accurate pathway coverage",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:46:36.696736+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pathway-database-querying/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The background set contains all molecules which can be detected in the experiment. For example, in transcriptomic studies, this consists of all genes or transcripts which can be quantified. In targeted metabolomics, the background set would contain all compounds assayed; in untargeted metabolomics, all annotatable metabolites (i.e., all the features in a dataset that can be annotated to a compound name or ID).",
      "asbval:note": "The paper directly addresses the scope: defining background sets based on detected metabolites and pathway membership for ORA.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pathway-database-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When preparing to run ORA on a metabolomics study: you have a list of detected metabolites from your experiment and need to determine which metabolites from the full pathway database should serve as the statistical background, and which pathways contain how many metabolites overa",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:46:36.696736+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
