      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "All simulations were performed using Python (v 3.8). Simulations with an element of randomisation were repeated 100 times, and results are reported as the mean of 100 random samplings of the simulation, alongside the standard error of the mean. For the conversion of compound names to KEGG identifiers, the MetaboAnalyst 4.0 [47] ID conversion tool was used. For Reactome, KEGG compounds were mapped to ChEBI identifiers using the Python bioservices package (v 1.7.1) [48].",
      "asbval:note": "Paper specifies Python version (3.8) and names specific package versions (bioservices v1.7.1, MetaboAnalyst 4.0, scipy), demonstrating reproducibility concerns. However, the paper does not present environment setup as a standalone task or workflow to be learned\u2014it is embedded in the Methods section as infrastructure for the actual research. The card frames this as a primary skill/task, which is scope drift from the paper's focus on ORA parameter sensitivity analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "python-environment-setup",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Configure a Python environment with specified version and dependencies to execute reproducible computational workflows.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:46:53.241370+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-output-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Using five publicly available datasets, we demonstrated that changes in parameters such as the background set, differential metabolite selection methods, and pathway database used can result in profoundly different ORA results... By means of in-silico simulations based on experimental datasets, all of the aforementioned variables have been shown to introduce varying levels of bias and uncertainty into ORA results",
      "asbval:note": "Paper performs in-silico simulations and generates figures/tables (Figs 2-6, Tables 1-2) comparing ORA results under varying parameters. However, the paper's focus is on demonstrating the SENSITIVITY and ROBUSTNESS of ORA to parameter changes, not on validating that re-executed code reproduces original results. The card frames this as a reproducibility/validation task, but the paper's actual use of simulations is for sensitivity analysis and parameter impact assessment. The paper does not explicitly address code reproducibility or output validation against reference publications.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-output-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validate that computational simulation outputs match expected results by comparing generated figures and tables against reference publications. This skill ensures reproducibility of pathway analysis simulations in metabolomics by systematically verifying that re-executed code pro",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:47:04.578537+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-output-validation/001",
