    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-parameter-variation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We investigated the effect of using a nonspecific background set, consisting of all unique compounds present in the KEGG organism-specific pathway set, compared to an assay-specific background set, consisting only of compounds identified and present in the abundance matrix of each dataset... In Fig 2C, we simulated a reduction in the number of compounds identified in the experiment... In Fig 2D, we aimed to demonstrate how changing the number of compounds in the background set but keeping the number of DA metabolites static affects the number of SEP.",
      "asbval:note": "Systematic variation of background set is a core methodological component.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-parameter-variation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "methods",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Vary background set size and composition (assay-specific vs. non-specific)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:47:15.900855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-parameter-variation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To investigate the effect of the list of input metabolites on the number of significant pathways, we used both BH FDR and Bonferroni methods for p-value adjustment and tested several cut-off thresholds (adjusted p \u2264 0.005, 0.05, or 0.1) for the selection of DA metabolites using each method.",
      "asbval:note": "Multiple testing correction methods and thresholds systematically varied.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-parameter-variation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "methods",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Vary differential metabolite selection thresholds (p-value and q-value cutoffs)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:47:15.900855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-parameter-variation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We simulated the effects of metabolite misidentification on ORA using KEGG pathways by replacing the true metabolites with false ones in two different ways: a) by similar molecular weight (20ppm window), and b) by identical chemical formula... we calculated the pathway loss and gain rate for each dataset at 4% simulated misidentification which, although there are few published estimates of misidentification rates in metabolomics studies [21], endeavours to simulate a representative scenario.",
      "asbval:note": "Metabolite misidentification systematically simulated across multiple rates.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-parameter-variation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "methods",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Simulate metabolite misidentification at varying rates (1\u20135% or 4% representative scenario)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:47:15.900855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-parameter-variation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To compare the effects of metabolite misidentification on the number and identity of significant pathways detected using ORA, we introduce two new statistics: the pathway loss rate and the pathway gain rate... The pathway loss rate refers to the proportion of SEPs present at 0% misidentification that are no longer present at f % misidentification, and the pathway gain rate refers to the number of SEPs not originally present at 0% misidentification which become significant at f % misidentification.",
      "asbval:note": "Pathway loss and gain rates explicitly defined and computed as performance metrics.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-parameter-variation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify false-positive and false-negative pathway rates (pathway gain rate and pathway loss rate)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T09:47:15.900855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/simulation-parameter-variation/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A clear discrepancy was observed in many of the pathway p-values when using the nonspecific vs. specific background set (Fig 2A)... Fig 3 shows an example of this procedure on the Labb\u00e9 et al. dataset... Heatmaps showing pathway loss rate and pathway gain rate at varying percentages of metabolite misidentification.",
      "asbval:note": "Multiple figures (scatter plots, bar charts, heatmaps) generated to visualize parameter sensitivity.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10_1371_journal_pcbi_1009105",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "simulation-parameter-variation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Generate plots and visualizations showing parameter sensitivity (e.g., scatter plots, bar charts, heatmaps)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
